[2026-03-12T15:55:48Z] [llm] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01GPQAkeQiyTHoLXuE7BrLCU","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01K66zdPfd8m3NfBXfXeF4LQ","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/workspace/docs/workflows.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2899,"cache_read_input_tokens":14049,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2899,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0165mefFg1Fyf6LaLScEQMXV","session_id":"b681cdd1-b2f2-4224-b489-8b848ed1cf19","uuid":"e889d570-d85f-413e-a825-4dc8ee5fceac"}
[2026-03-12T15:55:48Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01K66zdPfd8m3NfBXfXeF4LQ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Workflows\n     2→\n     3→Cloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4→\n     5→## Workflow Locations\n     6→\n     7→Cloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n     8→\n     9→**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) — Run inside a Docker\n    10→container via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\n    11→standard workflows for coding tasks.\n    12→\n    13→**Host workflows** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) — Run on the host machine as the daemon\n    14→process. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\n    15→dispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\n    16→point for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17→\n    18→A single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\n    19→uses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n    20→\n    21→| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n    22→|-------|--------------|---------|\n    23→| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n    24→| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n    25→| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n    26→\n    27→Only `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a legacy\n    28→single-function mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n    29→\n    30→The `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\n    31→object with the following fields:\n    32→\n    33→| Field | Required | Description |\n    34→|-------|----------|-------------|\n    35→| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n    36→| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n    37→| `title` | no | Short summary |\n    38→| `description` | no | Full description |\n    39→| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n    40→\n    41→The daemon picks the first task with status `open` (or empty, for backward\n    42→compatibility), runs `main` with that task ID, then runs `finalize` with the outcome.\n    43→Tasks are deduplicated within a configurable timeout window to prevent rapid\n    44→reassignment.\n    45→\n    46→The convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\n    47→file is a parse error.\n    48→\n    49→## Concepts\n    50→\n    51→| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    52→|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    53→| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    54→| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    55→| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    56→| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n    57→| done     | Built-in terminal step — successful completion                     |\n    58→| abort    | Built-in terminal step — failure with error reporting              |\n    59→\n    60→## Step Types\n    61→\n    62→Step type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    63→\n    64→**agent** (has `prompt`) — Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    65→to the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    66→container. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    67→\n    68→**script** (has `run`) — Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    69→any deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    70→\n    71→**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) — Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\n    72→until it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n    73→\n    74→A step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\n    75→parse error.\n    76→\n    77→## DSL Syntax\n    78→\n    79→```\n    80→workflow \"implement-feature\" {\n    81→  step code {\n    82→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    83→    container {\n    84→      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n    85→      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\"]\n    86→    }\n    87→    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n    88→  }\n    89→\n    90→  step check {\n    91→    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    92→    results = [pass, fail]\n    93→  }\n    94→\n    95→  step review {\n    96→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/review.md\")\n    97→    input = step.code.output\n    98→    results = [approved, changes_requested]\n    99→  }\n   100→\n   101→  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n   102→  code:success -> check\n   103→  code:fail -> abort\n   104→  code:retry_with_feedback -> code\n   105→\n   106→  check:pass -> review\n   107→  check:fail -> code:retry_with_feedback\n   108→\n   109→  review:approved -> done\n   110→  review:changes_requested -> code\n   111→}\n   112→```\n   113→\n   114→## Key Properties\n   115→\n   116→**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n   117→field makes it a script step.\n   118→\n   119→**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n   120→report. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n   121→\n   122→**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n   123→existing ones by rewiring — without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n   124→Cloche's self-evolution feature.\n   125→\n   126→**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n   127→wired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n   128→\n   129→## Wire Output Mappings\n   130→\n   131→Wires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\n   132→them as environment variables into the target step:\n   133→\n   134→```\n   135→step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   136→```\n   137→\n   138→The general form:\n   139→\n   140→```\n   141→FROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n   142→```\n   143→\n   144→Where `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\n   145→starting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n   146→\n   147→| Expression | Meaning |\n   148→|---|---|\n   149→| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   150→| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   151→| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   152→| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   153→| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   154→\n   155→If the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\n   156→structure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\n   157→value is converted to a string for env var injection.\n   158→\n   159→If two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\n   160→returns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\n   161→wires to different steps without conflict.\n   162→\n   163→## The `host {}` Block\n   164→\n   165→Host workflows support a `host {}` block at the workflow level to configure agent\n   166→defaults for agent steps running on the host machine. Keys are stored with a `host.`\n   167→prefix, analogous to the `container {}` block for container workflows.\n   168→\n   169→```\n   170→workflow \"main\" {\n   171→  host {\n   172→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   173→  }\n   174→  ...\n   175→}\n   176→```\n   177→\n   178→Supported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`. Step-level `agent_command` and\n   179→`agent_args` override the workflow-level `host {}` defaults. The agent command\n   180→resolution order for host agent steps is the same as for container agent steps:\n   181→step-level > workflow-level `host {}` > `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env var > default\n   182→`claude`.\n   183→\n   184→## Host Workflow Example\n   185→\n   186→A three-phase `host.cloche` with separate `list-tasks`, `main`, and `finalize`\n   187→workflows:\n   188→\n   189→```\n   190→# .cloche/host.cloche — runs on the host machine\n   191→\n   192→workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   193→  step fetch-tickets {\n   194→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   195→    results = [success, fail]\n   196→  }\n   197→\n   198→  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   199→  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   200→}\n   201→\n   202→workflow \"main\" {\n   203→  host {\n   204→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   205→  }\n   206→\n   207→  step prepare-prompt {\n   208→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   209→    results = [success, fail]\n   210→  }\n   211→\n   212→  step develop {\n   213→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   214→    results       = [success, fail]\n   215→  }\n   216→\n   217→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   218→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   219→  develop:success        -> done\n   220→  develop:fail           -> done\n   221→}\n   222→\n   223→workflow \"finalize\" {\n   224→  step push-for-review {\n   225→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n   226→    results = [success, fail]\n   227→  }\n   228→\n   229→  push-for-review:success -> done\n   230→  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n   231→}\n   232→```\n   233→\n   234→The daemon runs `list-tasks` to discover work (output is JSONL), picks an open task,\n   235→runs `main` with `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` set, then runs `finalize` regardless of outcome.\n   236→The `list-tasks` script writes one JSON object per line to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\n   237→The `main` workflow receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket.\n   238→The `finalize` workflow decides what to do based on the outcome (available via\n   239→`CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars).\n   240→\n   241→## Execution Model\n   242→\n   243→**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\n   244→container. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\n   245→wiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n   246→All steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n   247→\n   248→**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. A single\n   249→`host.cloche` file may contain multiple named workflows; the daemon orchestrates them\n   250→in three phases (list-tasks → main → finalize). Script steps run via `sh -c` with the\n   251→working directory set to the **main git worktree** (i.e. the main branch checkout), even\n   252→if the project directory is a linked worktree on a different branch. This ensures\n   253→host-workflow scripts from main are used for all runs. Workflow steps dispatch container\n   254→runs via the daemon's standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`,\n   255→`CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`, etc.) are injected into each step; `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` still\n   256→points to the actual project directory.\n   257→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0165mefFg1Fyf6LaLScEQMXV","session_id":"b681cdd1-b2f2-4224-b489-8b848ed1cf19","uuid":"7ee05380-86ed-4a6b-811f-db21375811a8"}
